  "summary": "Poirot interviews Mary DeLaur, the niece of the murdered Mrs. Asher, regarding her aunt's death. Mary explains that she moved to London at age eleven to live with her aunt following her mother's death. She describes Mrs. Asher's husband, a German man she calls \"my old devil,\" as a cheat and a beggar who frequently threatened Mrs. Asher with violence, including threats to cut her throat. Despite this, Mary notes that her aunt was a fearless, sharp-tongued woman who often intimidated her husband. Mary reveals that Mrs. Asher had very little money, only enough for funeral expenses, and had no other living relatives. When Poirot asks if her aunt received anonymous letters signed \"ABC,\" Mary states she was unaware of any. Poirot identifies himself as a private detective, gives Mary his card, and expresses a need for her potential future assistance.\n\nLater, at 5:30 PM, Poirot and Hastings travel to Andover to recreate the atmosphere of the previous night at Mrs. Asher's shop. A crowd has gathered at the scene. Inside the dim, dirty shop, a policeman explains that Mrs. Asher was found lying near a pile of items behind the counter. While the doctor could not determine the specific murder weapon, a pack of Player's cigarettes was found beside her. The policeman notes that a train schedule book was found open to the Andover-to-London page, suggesting the killer might not be a local resident. An initial search of the store and the counter yielded no fingerprints.",
